                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </section>

             <section class="article-section">
              <h2>Cross-Lingual Ambiguity</h2>
              <p>Interestingly, this ambiguity is specific to Latin-rooted languages. In other languages, the terms are distinct:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Arabic:</strong> Utarid (Planet) vs. Zi'baq (Metal).</li>
                <li><strong>Japanese:</strong> Suisei (Water Star - Planet) vs. Suigin (Liquid Silver - Metal).</li>
                <li><strong>German:</strong> Merkur (Planet) vs. Quecksilber (Metal).</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="article-section">
              <h2>Expert perspective</h2>
              <blockquote class="expert-quote">
                <p>"The word 'Mercury' is a perfect homonym storm. It bridges the physical (metal), the celestial (planet), and the divine (god). It is a linguistic artifact of how ancients connected fast-moving things."</p>
                <cite>— Dr. Elena Rossi, Historical Linguist</cite>
              </blockquote>
            </section>

